title: For Sale:  1935 Luger
location: West of Berthoud, Fort Collins, Colorado
postcontent:
I have a 9mm, “G” marked (1935), S/42 (Mauser), German Pistole Parabellum 1908 (Luger) with all matching serial numbers (X86, no suffix) except for the single clip that is numbered 585. (I have been told by a Luger dealer that a correctly numbered clip can be had, which is logical if you know the Luger numbering system.)  There is even an 86 on its firing pin, reciprocating mechanism and each wood grip just to mention what I remember.  This is a WWII war trophy passed down to me over 40 years ago. The inspectors numbers are IV 154 and S 92 as best I can tell. There is pitting on the barrel and left side plate. Local guns store owner said it was 65%. The bore is dull from the type of ammunition of its day and looks okay but not pristine. I have shot it and it functions properly.  This is a legitimate war trophy taken from a German who must have fought and not a staff officer.  As a war trophy it has never been registered to anyone.

I prefer to sell to a fellow Coloradoan to avoid the FFL, shipping hassles and costs.  Since this is over 50 years old I would consider sales direct to a C&R FFL holder under my terms.  I have many pictures and the sale is final.

For sale is what you see in the picture which is a Browing Hi-Power (aka P-35) made under contract from Fabrique Nationale, Belgium by John Inglis in Canada, a reproduction board shoulder stock and a 1953 Canadian holster, lanyard and two 13 round clips. Inglis reportedly (The Browning Hi-Power Automatic Pistol book) made 151,816 of these in the Mark I and Mark II patterns. Approximately 50,000 Mark 1's as this is, were made under what is called the Chinese contract, however few if any went to the Chinese because of WWII demand for side arms. The Mark I's are differentiated from the Mark II's by the slotted grip to accept a shoulder stock and the adjustable tangent sight versus the driftable only blade sight. The Mark I's are said to be in the most demand.
